title: Want To Buy:  WHO IS PAYING THESE PRICES?!?!?!
postcontent:
I ran 4 fake ads.  

.223/5.56 for a buck a round - NO RESPONSES IN THREE DAYS

A $400 handgun for $550 - 2 offers for $400/$425, one was a bit of an asshole about it too

Pmags for $30 - NO RESPONSES IN THREE DAYS

AR15 for $1500 - NO RESPONSES IN THREE DAYS

I made the ads for the most common overpriced items and used the average price I saw being asked.  So now that I know that NO ONE is actually paying the money, I wonder why these people are still asking these prices?  Do I just have bad luck and is everyone else actually getting attention?  I doubt it.  

It's a free country and you are welcome to ask whatever price you want for your belongings, but isn't enough enough at this point?  I just saw a PSA AR15 with about $600 worth of upgrades and extras asking over $3000!!!!! Ridiculous!!!!!  

Maybe I'm just naive enough to think people would be too smart to overpay by that much.  This website is such a useful tool and a wonderful idea, I just hate to see it cluttered with bullshit and abused by those thinking they can rip off their brothers in arms.  Such is life I guess.

FS/ST:  Common Sense and Decency, a package deal. Free to a good home.

title: For Sale:  SPF - .303 British - 13 rounds WW2-vintage tracer, 2 rounds ball COLLECTIBLE
postcontent:
here's a little leftover ammo lurking in the cabinet. I believe these to be .303 British tracers, 12 rounds with headstamp H (up arrow) N (indicates that the cartridges were made by the Royal Ordnance Factory, Hirwaun, South Wales, UK. This factory was set up as part of the 1939-45 war emergency expansion plan. It was involved in the production of .303 cartridges in only a very limited way and is known to have manufactured Tracer G Mk 2 (in cases dated 1943 and 1944)). The headstamp also bears the number 44 (for 1944 manufacture) and the letters GII, which indicates a Tracer G Mk 2 ("II" being a roman numeral 2)

One round is similar to the above, but its headstamp is a BE, for Royal Ordinance Factory, Blackpole, Worchester, UK, and it is a '43.

The bullets are unmarked, but they do have a red annulus around the primer indicating that it is a tracer. There is a tight crimp between the case mouth and the bullet.

The 13 rounds are in good to average condition for 70-year-old ammo, with some light corrosion, and are packed in what I believe is the original cardboard box -- though it has absolutely no markings.

Also included are two rounds of post-war ball ammo, a FN '51 and a POF '64.

I make no promises about the viability of this ammunition, though WW2-era ammunition is often just fine -- your mileage may vary. These would also likely be of some interest to a cartridge collector.

I'm in - I'm tired of ridiculous prices.

Please copy and repost to keep the message going.

Fellow firearm enthusiast, please help clean up this site from price gougers. Start flagging the overpriced items. We should be sticking together and fighting the folks attacking our second amendment rights here in Colorado, not taking advantage of each other.

When you see these gougers, and they are apparent flag them. They are not trying to make a fair profit but are doubling or tripling the price, simply click on the flag option, click overprice, and hit ok.

This message will likely be flagged by them within minutes and will disappear, so please help out. Copy this message and repost yourself later today and various times during the week.

If we show a uniform voice, they will eventually keep their hoarded stashes or come down in price. I am all about capitalism – I am not about taking advantage of others in a situation outside their control. Did we all feel the gas stations in New York charging $12 to $20 a gallon after the hurricane was fair – NO, and neither is the gouging going on right now.

Flag them. Help send the message by reposting this message. 

Your guns stores are getting firearms and ammo back in stock and most are selling at before panic prices.

No more $900 ARs for $1,800 to $2,000; no more USGI magazines that walk of military bases being sold for $30, nor more $700 AKs being sold for $1,500. Let freedom and fairness prevail!

title: For Sale:  These bills passed yesterday, only one step remains until it becomes law!!!!
postcontent:
Pay attention to your government folks, the following bills passed March 4:

The bills still need votes by the full Senate, which is controlled by Democrats.

A look at the bills and what they do:

- BACKGROUND CHECKS: House Bill 1229 would add a background-check requirement for many guns sold in private transactions. It passed a Senate committee in a 3-2 party-line vote. The Democratic-sponsored bill has already cleared the House.

- MAGAZINE LIMITS: House Bill 1224 limits gun ammunition magazines to 15 rounds. The Democratic-sponsored bill has cleared the House, and passed Senate Judiciary on a 3-2 party line vote.

- FIREARM BAN FOR DOMESTIC VIOLENCE OFFENDERS: Senate Bill 197 would expand a ban on gun ownership for people convicted of certain domestic-violence offenses. The bill passed the Senate Judiciary Committee on a party-line 3-2 vote Monday. One more committee vote awaits before the full Senate considers it.

- GUN LIABILITY: Senate Bill 196 adds legal liability for gun sellers and owners. The bill faced its first test Monday.

- GUNS ON CAMPUS: House Bill 1226 would end Colorado's unusual law barring public college campuses from banning concealed weapons. The Democratic-sponsored bill has already cleared the House.

- ONLINE GUN TRAINING: Senate Bill 195 would require people seeking concealed carry permits to take gun training courses in person. The bill faced its first legislative review Monday.

- BACKGROUND CHECK FEES: House Bill 1228 would revive fees for gun purchasers who need background checks. It passed a Senate committee in a 3-2 party-line vote. The Democratic-sponsored bill has already cleared the House.

I understand making a buck, but come on guys. Just because the crooks at ATP can sell .223 boxes for $17.99 doesn't mean you should on here. 

We are supposed to be brethren in this "sport" or "hobby," not gouging each other. If you have 1000 rounds of .223 and don't need it, pass it along for what you paid for it to a friend or something, quit flooding the market with this crap.

REFUSE to pay these astronomical prices and the prices will come down. This price gouging is ridiculous and you all should be ashamed of yourselves, both for selling it like that and for buying it at these enormous prices. The big box stores are selling it at reasonable prices and if the "scalpers" would stop buying it up to try and resell on here it would all come back and the price would come down. We are creating the false shortage, not the manufactures.

title: For Sale:  Pre Ban Gun Guy
location: south, Deep South....., Georgia, United States
postcontent:
Neighbor I've read your post about taking back our gun group and I vigorously support your right to get on here and say what you want. But I don't see your point. The people on here trying to turn guns at ridiculous prices aren't hurting me a bit. I read the ads, I don't buy the guns. If it bothered me to read the ads, I wouldn't read them.

But now this point does bother me..... These ads offend you. You get on here and raise hell because these people offend you in some manner. Gun grabbers want my guns because my guns offend them. Me having a gun offends them. Damned if I can figure out why. I've never done anything to them, but still they are offended.

I'm long winded I know, but here's the point. We as a people have to quit wanting to think for the other guy. We need to let the other guy think for himself. It made America great in the past, might still work. If we flag people today because WE think their prices aren't right, WHO are we going to flag tomorrow? Are we going to flag some guy because his guns  to cheap? Too old? Too used? This is a dangerous road to start down because it leads to exactly where we are now. We have this idiot in the whitehouse who believes we don't know what's good for us. He has to do our thinking for us. If we are old enough and still FREE enough to buy or sell a gun, we are old enough to figure out what we want to pay for it.

Having said that, I still defend your right to have your opinion and hope you accord me the same right to me.
